# Modular Consensus

The proof system must be modular, supporting pluggable "proofs" (PoW, PoS, hybrid). Accessible to all participants, not just whales and exchanges.

## Architecture

- In Rust: define a `ConsensusProof` trait that all proof mechanisms implement. Use dynamic dispatch (`Box<dyn ConsensusProof>`) at the orchestrator level.
- In C++: use abstract base classes with pure virtual methods for the same interface boundary.
- The consensus orchestrator selects and weights active proof modules based on chain configuration.

## Accessibility

- PoS minimum stake must be low enough for individual participants (not just large holders).
- PoW must remain CPU-friendly (RandomX lineage) to prevent ASIC/GPU monopolization.
- Provide a delegation mechanism so small holders can participate in PoS without running a full node.
- Reward distribution must be proportional to contribution, not just raw capital.

## Extensibility

- New proof types can be added by implementing the trait/interface -- no changes to the orchestrator required.
- Proof modules are registered at startup via configuration, not compile-time feature flags.
- Each proof module is independently testable with mock chain state.
